Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – The invasion of Ukraine by Russia on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of the Chinese New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is more robust than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and regard his confirmation as China's lifetime leader later this year as merely a formality.
After consolidating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario according to which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin embarked on realizing the dream of his life with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70s, Putin believes that if he wants to impose his印记 on Russian history, it is now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar to follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sensibility.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they are ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I established a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I established a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989 just before the Tian'anmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise to power, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to ruins. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a cunning operator of the KGB, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, it seems he has lost touch with reality.
He certainly miscalculated the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be in complete agreement with the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly brave resistance against an opponent that nothing seems able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was mistaken.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a deep anger.
But the Russian army performed poorly when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers.
The entrenched corruption in defense contract awarding has also played a significant role in its inadequate results.
However, instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to act without encountering any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and disregards all rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the electrical network supplying the Chernobyl nuclear plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In Mariupol under siege, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already accomplished wonders by reinforcing the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, it seems that Xi realized Putin is going it alone.
On March 8, one day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remained "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express the utmost restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will accede to Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
